Here's a complete example wrapping a REST API as an MCP server with stdio transport.

## Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Retrieve a user by their ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Create a new user with the given name and email.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("Display name for the user")] string name,
        [Description("Email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, email });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");

        logger.LogInformation("Creating user {Name}", name);
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/users", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## Program.cs — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|---------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the constructor (like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>` above) |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | DI services as method params alongside tool params |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes tool parameters from injected services. Types registered in the DI container (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<T>`) are resolved at runtime and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema sent to the LLM. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the model.

In the example above, `ApiTools` uses **constructor injection** via a primary constructor. The `AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(...)` call registers both `IHttpClientFactory` and a typed `HttpClient` that gets injected automatically. `ILogger<T>` is registered by default — no extra setup needed.
